¬ß Why ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We want to solve linear equations. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬ß Example ‚¶â
¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Suppose we want to find $x_1, x_2 ‚àà ùó•$ to satisfy the
    system of linear equations
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ \begin{aligned} ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ 3x_1 + 2x_2 &= 10, \text{ and} ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ 6x_1 + 5x_2 &= 20, ·ú∂ ‚¶â

      ‚Äñ \end{aligned} ‚¶â
    ‚¶â
    with constants $((3, 2), 10)$ and $((6, 4), 20)$. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ We can associate to the first equation an ‚ù¨equation for‚ù≠
    $x_1$ ‚ù¨in terms of‚ù≠ $x_2$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We call this ‚ù¨solving the first equation for $x_1$‚ù≠. ‚¶â
  ‚óá ‚¶ä
    ‚Äñ 3x_1 + 2x_2 = 10 \iff 3x_1 = 10 - 2x_2 \iff x_1 =
      \nicefrac{1}{3}(10 - 2x_2). ‚¶â
  ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Define $f_1: ùó• ‚Üí ùó•$ as $f_1(y) = \nicefrac{1}{3}(10 - 2y)$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Then $3x_1 + 2x_2 = 10$ if and only if $x_1 = f_1(x_2)$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ We have written $x_1$ ‚ù¨as a function‚ù≠ of $x_2$ and obtained
    a new equation. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The equation is not linear, however, as $f_1$ is not linear. ‚¶â
‚¶â

¬∂ ‚¶ä
  ‚Äñ Using the equation for $x_1$ in terms of $x_2$, we can
    substitute this equation into our second linear equation. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ The two linear equations hold if and only if
    ‚óá ‚¶ä
      ‚Äñ 6f(x_2) + 5x_2 = 20 \iff 20 - 4x_2 + 5x_2 = 20 \iff
        x_2 = 0. ‚¶â
    ‚¶â‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So the equations are satisifed if and only if $x_2$ is $0$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ If $x_2 = 0$,then $3x_1 = 10$ and $6x_1 = 20$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ Both of these are equivalent to $x_1 = \nicefrac{10}{3}$. ‚¶â

  ‚Äñ So we have that $x_1$ must be $\nicefrac{10}{3}$ and $x_2$
    must be 0. ‚¶â
‚¶â

